Laboratory Simulations of Abiotic Hydrocarbon Formation in Earth’s Deep Subsurface

INTRODUCTION

In recent years, methane and other light hydrocarbons with an apparently abiotic origin have been identified in an increasing number of geologic fluids on Earth.
(methane, have been identified in, number of fluids on Earth)
(hydrocarbons, have been identified in, number of fluids on Earth)

These compounds have been found in a variety of geologic settings, including seafloor hydrothermal systems, fracture networks in crystalline rocks from continental and oceanic crust, volcanic gases, and gas seeps from serpentinized rocks (for example,   Sherwood  2008;  2009;  ).
(compounds, have been found in, variety of settings)

Understanding the origin of these compounds has significant implications for range of topics that includes the global carbon cycle, the distribution of life in the deep subsurface , and the origin of life .

There are even claims that abiotic sources are major contributors to global hydrocarbon reservoirs .
(sources, are, contributors to hydrocarbon reservoirs)

While most experts are highly skeptical of such broad claims, it seems possible that at least some petroleum and gas reservoirs could contain hydrocarbons with an abiotic origin.
(experts, are skeptical of, claims)
(petroleum reservoirs, could contain, hydrocarbons)

Conceptually, there are two potential major sources of abiotic hydrocarbons to fluids in Earth’s crust.

First, abiotic hydrocarbons could migrate to the crust from deeper sources within Earth, through processes such as convective transport, grain boundary diffusion, or release of magmatic volatiles.
(hydrocarbons, could migrate to, crust)

Second, abiotic hydrocarbons could form in situ within the crust through reduction of inorganic carbon sources.

Potential substrates for carbon reduction include CO2 and CO in circulating fluids, and carbon-bearing solids such as carbonate minerals and graphite.
(substrates for carbon reduction, include, CO2 CO solids)

In either case, the ultimate source of the inorganic carbon may be primordial (i.e., from the mantle) or recycled from Earth’s surface.
(source of carbon, recycled from, surface)

This paper summarizes some of the recent laboratory experimental studies conducted to investigate potential pathways for the abiotic formation of organic compounds in subsurface geologic environments.
(paper, summarizes, some of laboratory studies conducted to investigate pathways for formation of compounds)

Experimental studies of abiotic organic synthesis are far too numerous for comprehensive coverage in a brief chapter.
(studies of synthesis, are numerous for, coverage in chapter)

Therefore, this overview focuses on the formation of methane (CH4) and other light hydrocarbons, since these are the compounds that have most frequently been attributed to an abiotic origin in natural systems.
(overview, focuses on, formation of methane)

In addition, only a selected subset of relevant studies is discussed, with the intent of providing a brief overview of current progress rather than an exhaustive review.

The discussion intentionally takes a critical perspective; this is done not to disparage the results of any particular study (which in most cases have represented the cutting edge of research on the subject), but to emphasize evolving paradigms and identify directions for future research.
(discussion, takes, perspective)

Because the mantle and crust provide very largely different environments for formation of abiotic organic compounds, they are discussed separately in the following sections.
(mantle, provide, environments)
(crust, provide, environments)

