This observation appears to be consistent, for example, with chemical analyses of magmatic volatiles trapped in vesicles within seafloor basalts, which are characterized by very high CO2/CH4 ratios (e.g., ).

At the same time, oxidizing conditions at Earth’s surface ensure that CO2 and bicarbonate are the predominant forms of dissolved carbon in seawater, in fracture-filling groundwater, and in shallow pore waters.

As a consequence, the predominant inputs of carbon to Earth’s crust from both above and below are in highly oxidized forms.

